The field of '''secular theology''', a subfield of [[liberal theology]] advocated by Anglican bishop [[John A. T. Robinson]] somewhat paradoxically combines [[secularism]] and [[theology]]. Recognized in the 1960s, it was influenced both by [[neo-orthodoxy]], [[Dietrich Bonhoeffer]], [[Harvey Cox]], and the [[existentialism]] of [[Søren Kierkegaard]] and [[Paul Tillich]]. Secular theology digested modern movements like the [[Death of God Theology]] propagated by [[Thomas J. J. Altizer]] or the philosophical existentialism of Paul Tillich and eased the introduction of such ideas into the theological mainstream and made constructive evaluations, as well as contributions, to them.<ref name="isbn0-664-22422-9">{{cite book |author1=Williams, Rowan |author2=Robinson, John |author3=Hall, Douglas J. |title=Honest to God |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |location=Louisville, Ky |year=2002 |pages= |isbn=0-664-22422-9 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref>
[[John Shelby Spong]] advocates a nuanced approach to scripture (as opposed to blunt [[Biblical literalism]] at the other end of the scale), informed by scholarship and compassion, which he argues can be consistent with both Christian tradition and a contemporary understanding of the universe. Secular theology holds that [[theism]] has lost credibility as a valid conception of [[God]]'s nature.<ref name="isbn0-06-067518-7">{{cite book |author=Spong, John Shelby |title=Rescuing the Bible from Fundamentalism : A Bishop Rethinks the Meaning of Scripture |publisher=HarperSanFrancisco |location=[San Francisco] |year=1991 |pages= |isbn=0-06-067518-7 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref> It rejects the concept of a [[personal God]] and embraces the status of [[Jesus Christ]], [[Christology]] and [[Christian eschatology]] as [[Christian mythology]] without basis in historical events.<ref name="isbn0-06-067546-2">{{cite book |author=Spong, John Shelby |title=Resurrection: myth or reality?: a bishop's search for the origins of Christianity |publisher=HarperSanFrancisco |location=[San Francisco] |year=1994 |pages= |isbn=0-06-067546-2 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref><ref name="isbn0-06-067523-3">{{cite book |author=Spong, John Shelby |title=Born of a Woman |publisher=HarperSanFrancisco |location=[San Francisco] |year= |pages= |isbn=0-06-067523-3 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref>
The movement chiefly came about as a response to general dissatisfaction with the Christian establishment's tendency to lapse into "provincialism" when presented with the "unusual" theological ideas common during the 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wesley.nnu.edu/wesleyan_theology/theojrnl/11-15/12-1.htm |title=THE PRESENT FRONTIERS OF WESLEYAN THEOLOGY |accessdate=2007-09-14 |work= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060903104412/http://wesley.nnu.edu/wesleyan_theology/theojrnl/11-15/12-1.htm |archivedate=September 3, 2006 }}</ref><ref name="isbn0-664-22355-9">{{cite book |author=Dorrien, Gary J. |title=The Making of American Liberal Theology: Idealism, Realism, and Modernity, 1900-1950 |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |location=Louisville, Ky |year= |pages= |isbn=0-664-22355-9 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref><ref name="isbn0-7546-3827-8">{{cite book |author=George Newlands |title=The Transformative Imagination: Rethinking Intercultural Theology |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |location= |year= |pages= |isbn=0-7546-3827-8 |oclc= |doi=}}</ref> The movement also suggested the legitimacy of seeking the [[holy]] outside the church itself. Thereby it suggests that the church did not have exclusive rights to divine inspiration. In a sense, this incorporated a strong sense of continuous revelation in which truth of the religious sort was sought out in poetry, music, art, or even the pub and in the street.{{Citation needed|date=January 2012}}
Certain other religions besides Christianity have developed secular theologies and applied these to core concepts of their own traditions. Notable among such movements has been the [[Reconstructionist Judaism]] of [[Mordecai Kaplan]], which understands God and the universe in a manner concordant with [[John Dewey|Deweyan]] naturalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.religion-online.org/showarticle.asp?title=1811 |title=Mordecai Kaplan's Pragmatic Religion |accessdate=2008-02-16|format = |work=}}</ref>
In [[Hinduism]], the [[Advaita]] school of theology is generally regarded as non-theistic as it accepts all interpretations of God or [[Ishvara]].
